ion_content": "**Evaluate the definite integral.**\n\n$\\displaystyle\\int^{2\\pi}_{\\frac{3\\pi}{2}}-4\\sin(x)\\,dx = $ [[☃ numeric-input 1]]", "hints": ["First, use the sine rule:\n\n$\\begin{align}\\displaystyle\\int^{2\\pi}_{\\frac{3\\pi}{2}}-4\\sin(x)\\,dx~&=~4\\cos(x)\\Bigg|^\\blueD{2\\pi}_{\\maroonD{\\frac{3\\pi}{2}}}\\end{align}$", "Second, plug in the limits of integration:\n\n$(4\\cdot\\blueD{\\cos(2\\pi)})-(4\\cdot\\maroonD{\\cos(\\frac{3\\pi}{2})}) = 4+0 =4$.", "The answer:\n\n$\\displaystyle\\int^{2\\pi}_{\\frac{3\\pi}{2}}-4\\sin(x)\\,dx~=~4$"], "widget_types": ["numeric-input"], "answer_data": {"numeric-input 1": {"type": "numeric-input", "answers": [{"maxError": null, "message": "", "simplify": "required", "status": "correct", "strict": false, "value": 4}]}}}, {"item_id": "a53373c8dfa459b39a8993d84516c675", "question_content": "**Evaluate the definite integral.**\n\n$\\displaystyle\\int^{-\\frac{5\\pi}{2}}_{-2\\pi}5\\cos(x)\\,dx = $ [[☃ numeric-input 1]]", "hints": ["First, use the cosine rule:\n\n$\\begin{align}\\displaystyle\\int^{-\\frac{5\\pi}{2}}_{-2\\pi}5\\cos(x)\\,dx~&=~5\\sin(x)\\Bigg|^\\blueD{-\\frac{5\\pi}{2}}_{\\maroonD{-2\\pi}}\\end{align}$", "Second, plug in the limits of integration:\n\n$(5\\cdot\\blueD{\\sin(-\\frac{5\\pi}{2})})-(5\\cdot\\maroonD{\\sin(-2\\pi)}) = -5-0 =-5$.", "The answer:\n\n$\\displaystyle\\int^{-\\frac{5\\pi}{2}}_{-2\\pi}5\\cos(x)\\,dx~=~-5$"], "widget_types": ["numeric-input"], "answer_data": {"numeric-input 1": {"type": "numeric-input", "answers": [{"maxError": null, "message": "", "simplify": "required", "status": "correct", "strict": false, "value": -5}]}}}, {"item_id": "bed0745740295f8895b4c00a4d33ad0c", "question_content": "**Evaluate the definite integral.**\n\n$\\displaystyle\\int^{6\\pi}_{\\frac{11\\pi}{2}}9\\sin(x)\\,dx = $ [[☃ numeric-input 1]]", "hints": ["First, use the sine rule:\n\n$\\begin{align}\\displaystyle\\int^{6\\pi}_{\\frac{11\\pi}{2}}9\\sin(x)\\,dx~&=~-9\\cos(x)\\Bigg|^\\blueD{6\\pi}_{\\maroon